The model itself is made of 3 parts, Korth 1 is the main body of the nozzle, Korth 2 is the rudder mount and the Rudder. I printed the model from PET with the Korth 1 laying on its face and the rudder oriented upside-down. The print was done using 0.4 mm nozzle and 0.15 mm z step. The final prints had slight ellipticity of 0.1 ~ 0.2 mm in the inner diameter.

description.text:
I'm currently incubating some bantam chicken eggs and wanted a candler so that I can see how the chicks are progressing.
It's dead simple to build, all you need is a miniature Osram LED globe, an old power cord, and a miniature on/off switch. I scrounged all of my bits from throw-outs, with the exception of the globe which will set you back a massive $5.
https://youtu.be/1DXmVdItJ4c

Print all the parts at 100% fill so that the unit has a little more weight to it. once printed you will want to disassemble the LED bulb, to remove the power supply you will need to melt the solder on the bulb contacts and gently pull the unit out.

Then place the LED panel inside the lamp holder and secure with two small self tappers, once secured, attach the lamp holder to the base unit using small countersunk self tapping screws.

Drill two holes for your wire through, then solder the wires onto the LED panel and feed them into the base unit.

It's now just a matter of soldering the wires from the LED panel to the power supply (checking that you have your polarity right) and you're done with the low voltage side of things.

Feed the mains cord through the labyrinth clamp, then solder one wire to your switch and the other to the input terminal on the power supply board, then simply connect the output from the switch to the second mains point on your power supply board and you're good to go. Don't worry about polarity as this is AC power so it doesn't matter.

Attach the power supply board in place using some double sided foam tape, then screw the base plate on.

Now all you need to do is select the correct sized lamp insert for your eggs and give it a go!

I've made a few different sized inserts, but you can also make up some of your own as they are removable and just slot in place.
This only took about an hour to knock up in 123D Design, so it's a bit rough and not very pretty, but it does work!

There is a small and large version. The large has an outside diameter 1.5 mm larger then the small. I use the small for tight places such as a 45° or 90° fitting. I use the large where there is plenty of room to grasp and turn. You can get the nut slightly tighter with the large version.
Both versions have a .5mm slit to provide a little spring. This allows it to slide easily over the nut and allows for expansion and contraction from summer heat to winter cold.

description.text:
Designed for:

  • Every standard drone frame with 30,5 x 30,5 mm FC support. Can be used for all sizes >= 3 inch
  • runcam swift micro 2.3mm

You need:

  • 4x M3 screws, length depends on your frame and spacers
  • 4x M3 hexagonal nuts

Files contained

  • STL with text "FPV FROG" on the back
  • STL without text
  • NEW: STL of the 5" frame it is not for printig, but for carbon cut in 5mm
  • untestet: STL for 2.1mm without text

Most motor shafts are higher than the pod. This means that the pod usually doesn't touch the environment in case of a crash. That's why the pod is easy to print in PLA. I fly with my 3" drone in the gym and the pod doesn't break. Weight is only about 8g. Cam angle is fix 45 degrees.

TPU I cannot recommend, the space between the components is very small, so they could destroy each other in case of a crash.

I recommend the following components. This makes a full featured build with telemetry, lua, osd and buzzer possible. You can use other parts, but they must be the same size or smaller.

Unify Pro HV Race

How to assemble ( pictures below ):

1) glue (CA) the hexagonal nuts into the hexagonal holes inside the pod
2) stick the antenna through the hole. Should be very tight, otherwise use glue
3) insert the VTX into the back of the pod, directly over the antenna cable
4) insert the cam into the front of the pod and and screw it tight
5) use double sided tape to mount XSR ontop the FC
6) if you have a buzzer, use double sided tape to mount it on the back of the cam
7) solder all together
8) mount the pod directly ontop your FC. Keep all cables inside
9) insert the screws from the bottom of your frame. Watch out for the length

If you want to have your craft name or call sign on the back of the pod, contact me!

title: SF Profile for Support using Alternate Extruder

description.text: This is a very hacked attempt at a SF 50 profile that will let you print your object on the right (T0) Replicator extruder while printing support using the left (T1).

A few notes:
I've used the alteration support_start and support_end gcode files in order to switch the extruder.  For some reason, however, T0 and T1 commands in these files don't work on the Replicator (FW v. 5.5) the way I expected.  Dualstrusion uses "M108 T0" / "M108 T1" to change toolheads -- which seems really odd to me -- so I've adopted that approach.  M108's that get issued out of these support_start and support_end files, however, don't make it intact into the ultimate gcode -- so I use T0 and T1 at the support_start and support_end stage, and then use the replace.csv support to create the right M108s... ugh.
Also, the Dimension plugin seems to break all of this, as it does not have any understanding of these being two different E values to keep track of.  I've tried hacking around with G92 statements, either resetting the extrusion length on toolhead swaps or "moving" the old value over.  This kind of works, but causes a long lag before extrusion starts -- resulting in missing areas of the print.  So the attached profile just turns Dimension off for now ... double ugh.
I'd love some feedback!  The next step for me is to actually use this profile to either print support in ABS at a much colder temperature than the print (to reduce bonding strength) or to start working on a PVA profile.

description.text: I upgraded my CR-10 to an aluminum mk8 extruder. This extruder leaves a large space between the extruder gear and the bowden. This adapter threads onto the inside of the hole where the bowden fitting attaches. You then install a pointed piece of PTFE tubing inside this part to span the remainder of the gap.

This is a small part with lots of detail in the threads so print at high resolution. Adhesion is an issue so I printed with a 3mm brim. I slowed everything including travel way down so that the part doesn't get knocked off the bed and also so the threads have enough time to cool as they print. It's small so still only takes a few minutes.

It's infinitely easier to install this with the extruder off the printer so just take it off and save yourself time/frustration. Install a ~10mm piece of PTFE tubing that is cut to a point on the end that meets with the gear and pulley. The tubing needs to fit tightly in this part so it doesn't work its way out, so you may have to fiddle a bit to get it seated. Make sure it's perfectly round and sand edges as needed to get it started.

Requires (2) 608 bearings, a bucket and a piece of 3/4" CPVC cut to fit.

The pipe is 3/4" CPVC which has an OD of ~22.3mm and 608 bearings with an OD of 22mm so the sleeve will slip on both snugly. Pipe is cut to length depending on your bucket since some are slightly different.

The trap works by spreading bait such as peanut butter on the middle of the pipe and adding 2-2.5 gallons of water in the bucket then add ramps or other method of making it so the mice can get to the ends of the pipe.

The mice walk out on the pipe to get the bait and it spins dropping them into the water to drown.

description.text:
This constructions is an easy and cheap way, to extend the storage capacity of your shelf/cupboard.

Why this part? Additional shelves for this open cupboard/shelf (why does english not distinguish between those two parts?) do cost 25 Euro for two pieces, and the whole shelf/cupboard itself was about the same price when i purchased it. I found that quite expensive and so i searched for a cheaper alternative.

I purchased some wooden boards for 4.75 Euro each (luckily already with the correct size to fit into the shelf frame), sanded them, put some bee wax on them, sanded again and designed and printed this mounting parts (4 for each wooden board).
They do have holes for screws, but i have not drilled holes into the boards yet - they seem to lay down quite save and stable on the shelf/cupboard.

comments.text: I think it is a neat idea.   But I would offer a word of caution for people using it.   Depending on the position this might be in while the key is in the running position, the weight from the other keys might be enough to cause the key to turn off while driving if it hits some bumps in the road.   If the engine shuts off you could lose power steering or power brakes or worse if it goes all the way off it might lock the steering column which would be very bad while driving.   I am not saying it will happen, but I don't want anyone trying to sue you for an accident when I know you mean well.
comments.author: TheBurnsBoys

comments.text: Cars have safety features to prevent this. For example, on the Audi Q5 You have to hold the lock button for three seconds, then press it three times, then hold it for another three seconds to shut the engine off while its running. The car will enable a "Lockdown" mode and you cannot unlock it without an Audi Certified Technician. With other cars you cannot shut the engine off while its running at all. You need to manually put the car in "park" or "neutral" and then remove the key from the car to shut the engine off. Even when you do this the steering column doesn't lock for 10 minutes after the driver has left the vehicle. You shouldn't need to worry about this, and anyway, this thing probably isn't designed for car keys...
comments.author: TheBurnsBoys

comments.text: I don't know where you live, but the high-tech features you mention are only on high-end cars that are very rare where I live. In every car I have ever driven, I can shut the engine down, remove the keys from the ignition and the completely mechanical and instantly activating steering lock will engage. On a few of them there is a button or lever to remove the keys from the column, which prevents the steering lock from engaging, but for most there's not. Of course I still can't see it occurring from this keyfob but our normal cars won't prevent it either.
